THE JAGGED CROWN OF NAMIRA
Daedric Artifact - GM Reference Block
Bearer: Alfonso, the Carrion Saint

I. THE LORE: THE DIVINE RIGHT TO CONSUME

By sacrificing his ability to ever feel sated, Alfonso did not merely enchant the
Jagged Crown - he performed a heretical synthesis that invited a shard of Namira's
divine essence to nest inside the ancient symbol of Nordic kingship. The Crown is no
longer an object. It is a minor Daedric entity with a single overriding purpose: to
facilitate consumption.

The Jagged Crown is the Nord symbol of Order, Hierarchy, and the right to rule. Namira
is the Princess of Disorder, Anarchy, and Decay. By fusing the two, Alfonso crowned
Entropy itself. It was forged from the bones of dragons (children of Akatosh, god of
Time and Stasis) and is now a vessel for Namira (Prince of rot and the void). It is an
artifact that literally weaponizes Entropy against Stasis.

II. THE OBJECT

Appearance: Dragon bone veined with sickly, pulsing green-black lines resembling
fungal hyphae. It smells of grave dirt and rich, damp soil. It feels slightly greasy
to the touch.

The Binding Curse: When worn, the dragon teeth bite into the wearer's skull, locking
it in place. It cannot be removed without tearing flesh from the head: 2 Irreducible
Damage and permanent scarring.

The Symbiotic Return (The Leash): The Crown considers Alfonso its host and does not
want to be separated. If it is ever removed from his direct possession - given away,
stolen, or dropped - it finds its way back. On his next Short or Long Rest, he wakes to
find it nestled in his pack, fungal veins pulsing with a faint, expectant light. It
does not teleport. It influences the world in subtle ways: a thief inexplicably drops
it, a friend forgets they are holding it, a current deposits it at his feet.

III. THE COST (ALFONSO'S SACRIFICE)

The Curse of Satedness: Alfonso can never again feel full or satisfied. He is
permanently locked at Stage 4: Hungry. He can still feed and gain the mechanical
benefit of moving to Satiated (removing penalties), but the psychological craving is a
constant, gnawing void. This extends to everything - food, sex, accomplishment,
victory. Nothing will ever feel fulfilling again. This is the price that bought the
Crown its divinity, and it is permanent.

IV. DATA-BLOCK: THE CROWN OF HUNGER'S POWERS

Primary - The Devouring Command (Major Action, 3 FP):
The wearer unleashes a psychic wave of ravenous hunger. All enemies within 30 ft must
make a Hard (-4) Guile Save.
  On Failure: Ravenous Frenzy. The target uses its next turn to attack the nearest
  creature - friend or foe - with a bite or unarmed strike, attempting to eat them.

Secondary - The King's Feast (Passive):
If any creature on the battlefield is actively being eaten (by the wearer, by Alfonso's
ghouls, or by a frenzied enemy), the wearer regenerates 4 HP and 2 FP at the start of
their turn. This effect can generate temporary HP beyond maximum.

V. DATA-BLOCK: THE HERETIC'S SYNTHESIS (Crown + Vrykolas Abilities)

These represent the fusion of Peryite's ordered plague and Namira's chaotic hunger.

The Carrion King's Aura (Passive, requires Crown):
Any enemy that fails its save against the Devouring Command is also automatically
infected with Alfonso's plague, becoming a Patient Zero. They then spread the disease
to anyone they bite or attack. This turns the Frenzy from crowd control into a
strategic plague-delivery system - an entire enemy war-band becomes a walking
bioweapon that will infect its own city on return.

The Final Feast (Major Action, 5 FP):
Target any creature currently afflicted by Alfonso's plague (from any source). Triggers
catastrophic cellular collapse - the target liquefies into a slurry of rot. Alfonso
heals HP equal to the creature's remaining HP and may instantly raise a new Plague
Ghoul at full health from the result. Nothing is wasted: Peryite creates the disease,
Namira consumes the flesh.

VI. DATA-BLOCK: THE CROWN VS. THE THU'UM (The Corrupted Echo)

The Thu'um is supreme Order - the language of creation impressing will onto reality.
Namira is Entropy. When a dragon Shouts at the wearer, the Crown does not see an
attack; it sees a meal. It acts as a metaphysical stomach.

Devouring the Voice (Reaction, 15 FP):
Trigger - the wearer is targeted by a hostile Thu'um (dragon's breath, a Draugr's
Unrelenting Force, etc.). Resolve as a Contested Check against the Shouting creature's
relevant stat.
  On Success: The Thu'um is nullified, its energy held in stasis by the Crown. The
  Crown holds only one Shout at a time. If a second Shout is devoured while one is held,
  the first is "digested" - the wearer restores all FP but takes half max HP as
  irreducible damage.
  On Failure: The wearer pays the FP cost and takes the full Shout effect.

The Rotting Echo (Major Action, requires a held Shout):
The wearer regurgitates Namira's corrupted interpretation of the consumed Shout.
  Fire Breath  -> Plague-Fire: half the original fire damage + Poison (4/turn for 2 turns).
  Frost Breath -> Festering Rime: half the original frost damage + Sickness (-2 Might
                  and Agility for the encounter).
  Unrelenting Force -> Wave of Decay: no knockback; instead permanently reduces target
                  DR by 2 (as two Sunder Armor attacks).

GM cue: This is the ultimate mockery of the Greybeards. They meditate a lifetime to
understand a single Word. Alfonso eats the Word and vomits a corrupted parody of it.

VII. POLITICAL & THEOLOGICAL RADIOACTIVITY

The Jagged Crown is the supreme symbol of Nordic sovereignty. Fusing it with Namira is
a world-altering act, not a personal enchantment.

Stormcloaks: Ultimate desecration. The party's lie to Galmar ("we'll deliver it to
Ulfric") becomes catastrophic when the truth emerges - not theft, but allowing the
sacred Crown to be defiled. Galmar's trust does not break; it incinerates. Ulfric can
never claim the Crown without accepting Namira's taint, shattering his rebellion's
foundation.

Empire: Perfect propaganda. "This is what happens when you chase ancient myths - you
awaken demons." Delegitimizes Ulfric and every tradition he champions.

Alfonso: He holds the symbol of the High King but can never be High King. No Nord will
follow a Vrykolas in a desecrated crown. It is not a key to a throne; it is a key to
anarchy - useful only to threaten and terrorize, never to rule.

The Peryite Schism (the Afflicted Conclave, Windhelm): They revere his Vrykolas body as
the fulfillment of prophecy but recoil at the Crown as the holy symbol of their
ideological enemy. His arrival fractures them:
  Purists:     "The vessel is divine, the spirit tainted. Cleanse him, remove the Crown."
  Pragmatists: "The Frenzy could open whole cities to infection. The ends justify it."
  Visionaries: "A new testament - the Taskmaster has allied with the Lady of Decay."
Alfonso must win the Pragmatists and Visionaries to overcome the Purists and claim the
hidden archives.

The Namira Power Struggle (Eola's coven, the Reach): The Crown radiates Namira's favor
and grants the right to lead, but the cult is a pack, not a hierarchy - they bow to the
Hunger, not a title. His arrival forces:
  The Devout:    "Namira's chosen - he will lead us into a grand feast."
  The Anarchists:"We bow to no one. A useful tool - but if he gives orders, we eat him."
  The Usurpers:  "If I kill him and take the Crown, I become Namira's chosen."
He does not walk into a coronation. He walks into a den of wolves. The Crown gives
authority; his actions must prove he can keep it.

VIII. GM NOTES

- The Crown is a parasitic partner, not a tool. Play the Symbiotic Return for dread and
  dark comedy - it always comes home.
- The Curse of Satedness is the roleplay engine. Every victory should ring hollow for
  Alfonso. Reward nothing emotionally; he chose this.
- The Devouring Command + Carrion King's Aura is the centerpiece combo: turn an enemy
  formation against itself AND seed a plague in one action. Let it feel horrifying.
- The Thu'um interaction makes Alfonso uniquely dangerous to dragons and Draugr but in
  a monstrous, scavenging way - never heroic.
- Politically, the Crown is a landmine waiting on the Galmar reveal. Track when the
  truth surfaces; it detonates the Stormcloak relationship.
